<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dailies Report `Political Surveillance' in South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dailies Report `Political Surveillance' in South </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3103103394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1016 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3103103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Intelligence Surveillance of `Civilian Government'" -- </F>
KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 31 (KCNA) -- It has been brought to 
light recently in South Korea that the rulers set up three watch 
posts around the house of former Chairman of the Democratic 
Party Kim Tae-chung in Seoul in 1979 to keep an eye on his every 
movement and have continued surveillance till today. 
  Papers here today say this act of the Kim Yong-sam group has 
proved that political surveillance over politicians is as 
vicious and persistent as under the military "regimes", though 
it claims a "civilian government" has been established in South 
Korea. 
  An analyst of NODONG SINMUN notes: 
  It is a serious matter that the traitor Kim Yong-sam 
continues vicious political surveillance over civilians, though 
he committed himself to build "a society where human rights are 
respected" and "stop intelligence surveillance" when taking the 
"presidential" seat. 
  With the traitorous Kim Yong-sam clique and such notorious 
intelligence tools as the "Security Planning Board" and the 
"secret affairs command" left alone, the South Korean people 
cannot evade being targets of intelligence surveillance. 
  A MINJU CHOSON commentary stresses that if human rights and 
democracy are to be guaranteed and the people are to live in 
peace in South Korea, all the political charlatans like the 
traitor Kim Yong-sam who stirs up horror and uneasiness and 
resorts to terrorism and plots must be removed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
