<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gallucci's Letter to DPRK Counterpart Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gallucci's Letter to DPRK Counterpart Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3103010894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0102 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3103010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 30 (YONHAP) -- Washington and 
Pyongyang recently exchanged letters clarifying their respective 
positions on international inspection of North Korea's nuclear 
facilities and a fresh high-level meeting. 
  Diplomatic sources here said Wednesday that Assistant 
Secretary of State for Military and Political Affairs Robert 
Gallucci sent a letter to North Korean Vice Foreign Minister 
Kang Sok-chu several days ago, saying a third round of 
high-level talks would not take place unless Pyongyang met two 
previously agreed conditions -- full inspection of nuclear sites 
at Yongbyon and an exchange of envoys between North and South 
Korea. 
  Gallucci and Kang headed their respective delegations to the 
previous two rounds of high-level U.S.-North Korean political 
negotiations. 
  The letter contained no fresh offers but urged Pyongyang to 
allow additional International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
checks of its nuclear facilities, while reaffirming the U.S. 
position on further talks, a source said. 
  Gallucci wrote the letter in reply to a missive sent by Kang 
in the middle of March. 
  In his letter, Kang urged Washington to hold a third round 
of 
talks as agreed, noting North Korea had permitted IAEA 
inspections. 
  South Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu told South Korean 
correspondents here that further high-level U.S.-North Korean 
talks would not be held until Pyongyang complied with the coming 
UN Security Council action, be it a resolution or a statement. 
  "I don't think it necessary for Washington to have prior 
consultations with Pyongyang regarding additional IAEA 
inspections, "He added, suggesting that the resumption of 
dialogue depends on whether Pyongyang changes its mind on the 
nuclear issue. 

</TEXT>

