Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Khieu Samphan Prepares To Return to Phnom Penh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Khieu Samphan Prepares To Return to Phnom Penh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK3103103294 Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA in Cambodian 31 
Mar 94 pp 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK3103103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA </F>
<F P=105>  Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Reports about the readiness of the Royal Government 
of Cambodia [RGC] and the Khmer Rouge to attend a meeting were 
heard while fighting was underway in northwestern Cambodia. Now 
there is a report that Khieu Samphan is prepared to return to 
Phnom Penh. 
  In Sopheap, the Democratic Kampuchea representative in Phnom 
Penh, has said: We are prepared to meet to solve this problem. 
Samdech Hun Sen, second prime minister of the RGC, was quoted as 
saying on 28 March that the government is leaving the door open 
for talks with the Khmer Rouge. Moreover, Prince Kromkhun 
Norodom Sirivut, deputy prime minister and minister of foreign 
affairs, said in Bangkok on 28 March: I hope the Khmer Rouge 
will listen to the advice of the king father of the nation and 
sit down at the negotiating table. 
  It is worth recalling that Prince Kromkhun Norodom Sirivut 
recently informed domestic and international reporters of the 
king's desire to see national reconciliation among Cambodians 
and an end to the bloodshed. 
  While the conflicting parties' intent to reach a peaceful 
solution is being heard, there is also a rumor that Khieu 
Samphan, the nominal leader of the Khmer Rouge, will soon return 
to Phnom Penh. The Democratic Kampuchea official did not 
confirm or deny this report. 
  It is known that His Majesty King Norodom Sihanouk and the 
queen will return to Phnom Penh on 8 April. Prince Kromkhun 
Norodom Sirivut says he hopes that talks with the Khmer Rouge 
will resume at that time. 
  The talks have been adjourned since mid-January following a 
series of futile talks between First Prime Minister Prince 
Krompreah Norodom Ranariddh and Khieu Samphan. Nevertheless, 
Samdech Hun Sen has said: Our position remains unchanged. We 
are keeping the door open and are considering the possibility of 
such a meeting when the king returns. 
  Khieu Samphan's whereabouts are currently unknown. A 
military source, however, has disclosed that Pol Pot is staying 
in Kum Rieng village, only a few kilometers north of Pailin. He 
fled Pailin two days before the stronghold fell to the 
government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

