<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Infrastructure Projects Popular With Investors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    * Infrastructure Projects Popular With Investors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94SE0087A Kuala Lumpur BERITA HARIAN in Malay 12 Feb 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> 94SE0087A </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERITA HARIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Malay </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The property sector will continue to be the first 
choice of investors throughout 1994 because of the various land 
and building development projects now being implemented and the 
large number of projects scheduled for this year. Several 
market analysts predict that spending in the land and building 
sector in Malaysia will remain high and that construction will 
continue to experience rapid double-digit growth over the next 
three years. 
  One analyst said that construction of the Kuala Lumpur 
International Airport (KLIA) at Sepang alone will cost 8 billion 
ringgit. The giant project will spawn many construction 
contracts worth more than any in the past. 
  The analyst listed IJM Corp. Bhd. [Limited], Pelecon 
Engineering Bhd., Sungei Way Holdings Bhd., and United Engineers 
Malaysia Bhd. as the three construction companies best prepared 
to compete for the contracts. He said the selection of a 
company will be based on the company's capabilities as shown by 
previous accomplishments, financial and management performance, 
and preparedness from the aspect of capital and skills. 
  Another analyst said that the property "counter" will 
continue to have bright prospects for investment portfolios 
because the industry will be affected by a positive synergism. 
  He said current factors consist of six principal projects 
now 
under way: a series of roads worth 1 billion ringgit in the 
Kuala Lumpur area, roads and highways in the eastern part of the 
Peninsula (500 million ringgit), Tenaga Nasional [National 
Power] Bhd. electric power plant and transmission cable projects 
(11 billion ringgit), a Telekom Malaysia Bhd. project (8 billion 
ringgit), a water supply project (2 billion ringgit), a twin 
runway project, and KTM [Malayan Railways] Bhd. electric trains 
(1.2 billion ringgit). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

