<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Discusses UN Debate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman Discusses UN Debate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   CM3103113694 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1205 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> CM3103113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1205 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 31 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the 
DPRK Foreign Ministry today answered questions put by KCNA about 
the attempt of the United States to justify its campaign for 
pressure on the DPRK by distorting facts with the allegation 
that the DPRK did not allow a proper inspection for the 
continuity of safeguards. 
  [KCNA] The United States is now justifying its campaign for 
pressure on the DPRK with the allegation that the DPRK did not 
allow a full inspection by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA]. Please tell me about the truth in detail. 
  [Spokesman] The United States is contending that the DPRK 
must accept a full IAEA inspection, alleging that the recent 
inspection of the DPRK's nuclear facilities by the IAEA was not 
satisfactory. But this is quite contrary to the fact. 
  We are in a unique status after a temporary suspension of 
the 
effectuation of our declared withdrawal from the nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) [haengmugi chonpabangji choyak 
taltoe hyorok palsaengul imsi chongjihan tuksuhan chiwie innun 
urinun]. So we are not obliged to accept a full inspection by 
the IAEA pursuant to the safeguards agreement. Moreover, we have 
never agreed with the United States and the IAEA on it. 
  We agreed with the United States and the IAEA only to an 
inspection for maintaining the continuity of safeguards. 
  When the scope of the IAEA inspection was agreed upon at the 
DPRK-U.S. contact in New York in late December last year, the 
sides promised that it should be a strictly limited inspection 
[chehan sachal] for the maintenance of the continuity of 
safeguards, not a routine and ad hoc inspection [chonggi mit 
pijonggi sachal] pursuant to the safeguards agreement. 
  At that time, the U.S. side asked the DPRK not to announce 
to 
the world that it would be a limited inspection to save its face. 
  At the New York contact in February, the U.S. side clarified 
its position that if an IAEA inspection was made, it would come 
out to the third round of talks with the DPRK, irrespective of 
the results of the inspection. 
  The United States which had promised a limited inspection 
and 
asked the DPRK not to open it to the public and stated it would 
have talks with the DPRK, irrespective of the results of the 
inspection, is now urging the DPRK to accept an additional 
inspection, charging that it refused to accept a full inspection 
by the IAEA pursuant to the safeguards agreement. This is a 
self-contradictory act. 
  This fully shows how faithless the United States is. 
  [KCNA] What does the United States really seek in reversing 
the DPRK-U.S. agreed conclusions and kicking up a row of 
pressure on the DPRK? 
  [Spokesman] I think it was motivated by the U.S. trite 
hostile policy toward the DPRK [kutaeuiyonhan taejoson choktaesi 
chongchaek]. 
  Admittedly, we have honestly discharged our obligation 
according to the agreed conclusions reached between the DPRK and 
the United States at the New York contact. 
  The United States, however, had made false promises and it 
took no action in actuality. 
  Nevertheless, the United States is resorting to pressure on 
the DPRK and war provocation moves, alleging that the DPRK has 
failed to implement the agreement. How can it be construed 
otherwise? 
  As we have declared more than once, if the third round of 
the 
DPRK-U.S. talks had been held and the nuclear issue resolved in 
a package deal [haengmunjeui ilgwal tagyorani songsa 
toeoddoramyon], the IAEA's routine and ad hoc inspections of the 
DPRK would have been resumed and the exchange of special envoys 
between the North and the South would have been possible. 
  But the United States intentionally foiled the third round 
of 
the talks, which would be the key to the solution of the nuclear 
issue, setting unjustifiable preconditions. This clearly proves 
that the United States has no intention to resolve the nuclear 
issue through negotiation and it is only using the talks to 
stifle the DPRK and, further, promote its strategic interests in 
the Asia-Pacific region. 
  [KCNA] Now that we have undergone an inspection enough for 
the continuity of safeguards as we had agreed with the IAEA, the 
UN Security Council has no reason or justification to discuss 
our issue, does it? 
  [Spokesman] Of course not. The continued discussions of our 
issue at the UN Security Council under this situation only give 
the impression that the international organisation is courting 
the favor of a country. 
  And this may be a living example that even international 
organisations are used for the attainment of the U.S. egoistic 
aim. 
  The IAEA Secretariat made haste with the adoption of a 
"resolution" distorting the results of the inspection after 
carrying out the inspection of enough scope for the continuity 
of safeguards, and now the UN Security Council is discussing our 
issue. All this is manipulated behind the scene by the U.S.-led 
forces to stifle [apsal] the DPRK. 
  If the UN Security Council follows the United States, it 
will 
seriously harm its authority as an international organistion 
whose lifeblood is impartiality. 
  If the UN Security Council truly wants to discharge its 
mission, it must not argue about the DPRK, the victim, but argue 
about the acts of the United States, the assaulter, and put 
pressure on it. 
  If the UN Security Council, departing from the principle of 
impartiality, defends the United States, the assaulter, for the 
reason that it is a big power and puts unwarrantable pressure 
upon the victim for the reason that it is a small country, the 
small countries will no more trust the United Nations. 
  The UN Security Council must not be used as a rostrum for 
putting unreasonable pressure upon the DPRK over the nuclear 
issue. 
  [KCNA] What measures are needed in your opinion for paving 
the way for a solution to the nuclear issue? 
  [Spokesman] The United States must no more pursue a hostile 
policy toward Korea, first of all. 
  Since the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula was caused 
by 
the U.S. policy to stifle our system, as mentioned above, if it 
is to be solved, the United States must take measures first for 
removing the nuclear threat to us and giving up the hostile 
policy. 
  Still today when the nature of its anti-DPRK moves has been 
brought to light, the United States is resorting to the row of 
pressure against us, calling for UN "resolution" and the like. 
This cannot be justified with anything. 
  The South Korean authorities must ponder over the lot in 
which they would find themselves while running about reckless, 
not knowing their position as now. 
  The United States must sincerely implement the agreed 
conclusions reached at the contact with us. 
  It is a violation of the DPRK-U.S. agreed conclusions and a 
mockery of our sovereignty for the United States to demand a 
full inspection of the DPRK by the IAEA and the exchange of 
special envoys between the North and the South, not implementing 
its own obligations at all. 
  Pressure can never be a way of the solution of the problem 
but it only makes the situation complicated. 
  It is nonsensical to urge us to accept an additional 
inspection since we have already accepted, fairly and squarely 
[chongjong tangdanghage], an inspection of a scope enough for 
the continuity of safeguards according to our agreement with the 
United States and the IAEA. 
  If the United States continues to misuse [agyong] our 
sincere 
efforts to resolve the nuclear issue, we would no longer pin 
hope on the DPRK-U.S. talks and will counter [massonagal gosida] 
any pressure to the end. 
  But if the United States put a stop to the international 
pressure campaign against the DPRK and proceed with the 
reestablishment of the foundation of the DPRK-U.S. talks we 
would not oppose a negotiated solution to the issue through 
negotiations. 
  Consistent is our position to resolve the nuclear issue 
through dialogue. 
  The future developments and a peaceful solution to the 
nuclear issue entirely depend on the attitude of the United 
States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

