<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fuji Photo Criticizes U.S. Antidumping Tariffs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fuji Photo Criticizes U.S. Antidumping Tariffs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3103015194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0046 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103015194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 31 KYODO -- Fuji Photo Film Co. on 
Thursday [31 March] criticized the U.S. Government's decision to 
impose stiff penalty tariffs on its color photographic paper 
sold in the United States. 
  Washington imposed tariffs of 360.95 percent Wednesday, 
based 
on a preliminary ruling by the Commerce Department that Fuji 
Photo Film was selling the products in the U.S. at less than 
fair market value. The decision stems from a petition filed by 
Eastman Kodak Co. of the U.S., charging the Japanese company 
with selling photographic paper in the U.S. at only a quarter of 
the prices it charges for identical products in Japan. 
  A Fuji Photo Film executive said, "it is Eastman Kodak that 
can decide prices in the U.S. market and we cannot understand 
the allegation that Fuji is dumping its products to harm the 
U.S. industry." Regarding the huge margin of the penalty 
tariffs, he said the way they were calculated was not clear. 
  As reasons for the lower prices of the products in the U.S., 
the official cited the yen's appreciation against the dollar, 
sales incentive rewards, and costs of other services for 
processing laboratories in Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

