<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators Join Signature Campaign for Burma </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Legislators Join Signature Campaign for Burma </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3103063594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0543 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103063594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 31 KYODO -- A record number of 
Japanese Diet members have signed a letter to be sent to the UN 
chief calling for freedom for Nobel peace prize winner Aung San 
Suu Kyi and civilian rule in Myanmar [Burma], the Burmese 
Association in Japan said Thursday [31 March]. 
  Of a total of 763 Diet members, 403 have already put their 
signatures to a petition to be sent to UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, the association said in a press release. 
Similar signature campaigns are being carried out in 108 
countries around the world, it said. 
  A copy of the letter said the legislators will urge the 
United Nations to do all in its power to see that Suu Kyi and 
all political leaders are unconditionally released. It also 
called for a "swift and complete implementation of a transition 
to civilian rule." 
  The group hopes to receive 500 signatures of Diet members 
through the good offices of United Social Democratic Party 
leader Satsuki Eda by the time the letter is sent, said 
association president Win Naing. 
  This is the second such letter to Butrus-Ghali. The first 
plea by 374 Diet members was delivered to the secretary 
general's office in March 1993 by Eda. 
  Last April 422 Diet members urged the government to put 
pressure on Myanamr for Suu Kyi's release. 
  A founder of the National League for Democracy (NLD) which 
won the 1990 election by a landslide, Suu Kyi has been under 
house arrest since July 1989. She was scheduled to be freed 
next July but the ruling military junta extended her detention 
period for another year. 

</TEXT>

