  [Text] Tokyo, March 31 KYODO -- Prime Ministers Morihiro 
Hosokawa of Japan and Begum Khaleda Zia of Bangladesh issued a 
joint press statement Thursday [31 March] saying Zia's official 
visit to Japan has served to strengthen bilateral relations. 
The statement said that in summit talks on Tuesday, Hosokawa 
hailed Zia's efforts for democratization and economic 
development. 
  Zia outlined her government's achievements in consolidating 
democracy, implementing economic reforms and pursuing social and 
economic development, it said. She explained her policies aimed 
at alleviating poverty, creating rural employment and improving 
primary education and basic health care. 
  Zia expressed gratitude for Japan's economic assistance to 
date and for its new offer to cofinance a major bridge spanning 
the Jamuna River, which should serve to promote economic 
development in the northern areas of Bangladesh. 
  The statement said Hosokawa urged Bangladesh to take care to 
ensure that Japan's official development assistance (ODA) is 
implemented promptly and smoothly. 
  It said the two countries agreed to start negotiations on 
concluding a bilateral agreement concerning the encouragement 
and protection of investment. 
  Zia, who arrived in Japan on Monday for a five-day official 
visit, reconfirmed Bangladesh's support for the permanent 
membership of Japan on the UN Security Council, the statement 
said. 

