<H3> <TI>   1993 Loans, Aid to Other Countries Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    1993 Loans, Aid to Other Countries Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3103102494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1003 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103102494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 31 KYODO -- Japan loaned more than 1 
trillion yen to 27 countries in fiscal 1993, a senior Foreign 
Ministry official said Thursday [31 March]. It also provided a 
record high of 999 million yen in small-scale aid grants to 54 
nations and one region, the official said. 
  Japan extended a total of 1.034 trillion yen in loans, down 
13 percent from the previous fiscal year, the official said. Of 
the loans that covered 111 projects in 27 countries, 812 billion 
yen, or 80 percent, went to Asia, the official said. 
  Japan extended loans totaling 6.5 billion yen to Kyrgyzstan, 
making it the first Central Asian nation to receive Japanese yen 
loans. Japan also extended a 52.3 billion yen loan to Vietnam 
for the first time. 
  Yen loans for environmental projects reached 148.7 billion 
yen, the official said. 
  Japan's small-scale grassroots assistance to recipients such 
as nongovernmental organizations, medical and educational 
institutions was up 42.8 percent from the previous year. 
  The aid covered 258 projects in the educational, medical and 
environmental fields, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4394 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas062_a_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-062 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yen's Strengthening Against Dollar Criticized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yen's Strengthening Against Dollar Criticized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3103073494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0716 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103073494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 31 KYODO -- A senior government 
official said Thursday [31 March] the yen's recent spurt against 
the U.S. dollar does not reflect the economic fundamentals of 
Japan. Hideaki Kumano, vice minister for administrative affairs 
at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI), also 
said the yen's advance will have a negative impact on both the 
Japanese and global economies. 
  The Japanese currency has steadily gained ground in recent 
sessions on speculation that Washington may talk up the yen to 
extract further concessions from Japan on stalled bilateral 
trade talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

