<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation To Import U.S., China, Australia Rice </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation To Import U.S., China, Australia Rice </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2903120994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1107 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2903120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 29 KYODO -- The Food Agency announced 
Tuesday [29 March] that Japan will import another 150,000 tons 
of rice from the United States, Australia and China by the end 
of August, to bring the total amount of emergency imports of the 
grain to 2.65 million tons this year. 
  The emergency step is aimed at making a sufficient supply of 
rice available to consumers in the preharvest period, agency 
officials said. Japan suffered the worst rice harvest in 
postwar days last year, necessitating the emergency imports. 
  The officials said blended rice will be sold at a ratio of 
70 
percent domestic rice to 30 percent imported rice from 
September, with domestic rice taking a dominant share compared 
with the 30-70 percent ratio expected in April through July. 
  From October, consumers are expected to buy domestic brands 
almost entirely, they said. 

</TEXT>

