<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electric Appliance Store To Stop Rice Sales </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Electric Appliance Store To Stop Rice Sales </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3003061394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0550 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 30 KYODO -- An electric appliance 
discount chain store without a license to sell rice decided 
Wednesday to call off the planned rice sales next Sunday [3 
April] after discussing the matter with the Food Agency and the 
Tokyo Metropolitan Government. "The three sides concluded the 
talks by deciding we should donate the rice," said Toshio 
Miyaji, president of the Tokyo-based Jonan Denki Co. 
  About 15 tons of rice the company has bought from farmers in 
Ogata, Akita Prefecture, will be donated to old people's homes 
with the Tokyo Metropolitan Government helping in its 
distribution. 
  Jonan Denki's store in Tokyo's Suginami ward sold rice last 
Sunday in defiance of the Food Agency's warning that selling 
rice without a government license is a violation of the Food 
Control Law. About 2,000 people lined up to buy about 12 tons 
of brand-name rice produced in Ogata. 
  The bad weather last year has made domestically grown rice 
scarce, and consumers have been queuing and paying high prices 
for domestic rice since February. 

</TEXT>

