<F P=101> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Parliamentary Representatives Visit Hanoi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Czech Parliamentary Representatives Visit Hanoi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Review Economic Agreements </H4>

<F P=102> AU3103161994 Prague CTK in English 1533 GMT 31 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3103161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi, March 31 (CTK) -- Parliamentary 
representatives of Vietnam and the Czech Republic are reviewing 
economic and trade agreements before Czech Foreign Minister 
Josef Zieleniec's visit to Vietnam, Vietnamese deputies told CTK. 
  A Czech parliamentary delegation is currently on a four day 
visit to Vietnam, led by parliament chairman Milan Uhde. 
  The need to update existing agreements has arisen from the 
Czech Republic having undergone substantive changes in economy 
and foreign trade, a subject discussed with the Vietnamese side 
by Czech Industry and Trade Minister Vladimir Dlouhy during his 
visit to Vietnam last November. 
  An agreement is being drawn up on settling the Vietnamese 
debt worth 92,3 million XTR (interchangeable rubles) and $7.4 
million. 
  Vietnamese deputies agreed with the Czech proposal that 
bilateral agreements on double taxation and the protection of 
investments be signed, Czech deputy Jan Krycer said, adding that 
use might be made of the knowledge and expertise of the 
Vietnamese who had received Czech training and worked in the 
Czech Republic. 

</TEXT>

