<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: No Evidence of DPRK Nuclear Weapons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: No Evidence of DPRK Nuclear Weapons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404081394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0743 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0404081394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 4 KYODO -- Japan's vice minister of 
defense said Monday [4 April] Tokyo has no evidence that North 
Korea possesses nuclear weapons as suggested by Washington. "We 
cannot confirm this," Shigeru Hatakeyama told a news conference 
referring to U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry's remarks in a 
Sunday NBC program that North Korea has already built two 
nuclear weapons. 
  Asked whether he believes that Pyongyang's new mid-range 
missile capable of reaching most of Japan can be used with 
nuclear warheads, Hatakeyama said he would not rule out such a 
possibility "in the future." 
  "At the present stage, however, all we can say is that this 
would be rather difficult," the vice minister said. 

</TEXT>

