<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to UN on China's Role in DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy to UN on China's Role in DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404125494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1234 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0404125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Toyama, April 4 KYODO -- Hisashi Owada, the Japanese 
ambassador to the United Nations, stressed Monday [4 April] that 
China's role is essential in bringing the North Korean nuclear 
problem to a peaceful resolution. In a speech to an 
international forum, Owada said the major powers must have 
cooperative ties to maintain international order in the 
post-Cold War era. 
  A good example, he said, is the cooperation of China in the 
standoff over North Korea's refusal to allow full international 
inspections of its nuclear facilities. 
  Commenting on Japan's bid to become a permanent member of 
the 
U.N. Security Council, Owada said the focus should be on how 
Japan can aid the United Nations in maintaining global order 
rather than on simply winning permanent membership of the 
Council as a symbol of its powerful status. 

</TEXT>

