<H3> <TI>   ROK's Foreign Minister Han Arrives 3 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK's Foreign Minister Han Arrives 3 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0304113494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1010 GMT 3 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0304113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Yi Kang-tok from Tokyo] </F>
  [Text] ROK Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, who arrived in 
Tokyo today after completing a visit to the United States, held 
talks with Japanese Foreign Minister Hata. They decided that 
the two nations will continue efforts for a solution to the 
North Korean nuclear issue through dialogue. 
  The foreign ministers of two countries shared the view that 
for North Korea to resolve its nuclear issue through 
negotiations, North Korea should first accept the nuclear 
inspection by the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] and 
should respond to North-South dialogue, and that China is 
playing an affirmative role for a change in the North Korean 
attitude. 
  During the talks, the foreign ministers of two nations 
shared 
the understanding that in the event that North Korea refuses 
IAEA nuclear inspection in defiance of the statement by the UN 
Security Council president, hard-line countermeasures, including 
UN applied sanctions, will be inevitable. Thus, it is likely 
that the two foreign ministers discussed concrete measures for 
sanctions. 
  At the same time, Foreign Ministers Han Sung-chu and Hata 
agreed to work out promptly the follow-up programs discussed 
during the ROK-Japan summit last month, including the plan to 
support permanent repatriation of Korean compatriots in Sakhalin. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu will meet with Japanese Prime 
Minister Hosokawa tomorrow and will explain to him the result of 
the ROK-PRC summit and joint measures on the North Korean 
nuclear issue, which were discussed between the ROK and the 
United States during his visit to the United States. 

</TEXT>

