<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commends U.N. Security Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commends U.N. Security Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0304134294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1318 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0304134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 3 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata and his South Korean counterpart Han Sung-chu agreed Sunday 
that China has a vital role in resolving the North Korean 
nuclear issue, Foreign Ministry officials said. Hata and Han 
commended the U.N. Security Council for leading China to back 
its statement urging North Korea to accept unimpeded inspections 
of its nuclear facilities, the officials said. 
  The foreign ministers gave "positive appraisal" to the 
statement adopted unanimously on Thursday by the 15 member 
states of the U.N. Security Council, they said. The statement 
of Security Council President Jean-Bernard Merimee of France was 
adopted after the United States dropped its bid to have the 
Security Council adopt a binding resolution. 
  It urged North Korea to allow International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) inspectors to complete an uncontrolled check of 
its nuclear facilities, while expressing concern that an IAEA 
team was barred from inspecting a radiochemical laboratory 
earlier this month. 
  After the Security Council members agreed to comply with 
Chinese demands to eliminate any language about sanctions, 
China, North Korea's traditional ally, agreed to endorse the 
mildly-worded, nonbinding statement. 
  The two foreign ministers confirmed their intention to 
monitor how the North will respond to the Security Council's 
demand to have it accept unhampered inspections within a month, 
the officials said. 
  Han will hold talks with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on 
Monday before flying back to Seoul from a three-country trip to 
help solve the nuclear proliferation issue, they said. Before 
flying to Tokyo, Han sought cooperation from both the U.S. and 
China. 

</TEXT>

