<H3> <TI>   Takemura on Opportunity for Hata-Kantor Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Takemura on Opportunity for Hata-Kantor Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404042494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0318 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0404042494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 4 KYODO -- The government plans to 
send Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata to a ministerial meeting of 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade in Marrakech, 
Morocco, from April 12 through 15, the chief cabinet secretary 
said Monday [4 April]. 
  Masayoshi Takemura told reporters Hata will have an 
opportunity for talks with U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor about ways to reopen stalled trade negotiations between 
Japan and the United States. "We hope this will provide us a 
chance to achieve a breakthrough," Takemura said. 
  Takemura denied a news report that Japan and the United 
States will have unofficial talks as early as this week aimed at 
breaking the stalemate in bilateral trade negotiations. "We 
haven't decided on such a specific plan," he said. 
  Takemura also said that Tokyo will continue to seek a 
breakthrough in the stalled "framework" trade talks with 
Washington while carrying out a market-opening package announced 
last month. 
  The bilateral trade talks have been deadlocked since 
February 
11, when Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. President 
Bill Clinton failed to reach agreement on a U.S. demand for 
numerical targets to gauge the openness in Japanese markets. 
  A Japanese newspaper reported Sunday that Japan will send a 
senior official to Washington as early as this week to hold 
unofficial talks in hopes of breaking the impasse over the trade 
negotiations. 

</TEXT>

