<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kankaku Firm To Be Fined for `Dubious' Deals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kankaku Firm To Be Fined for `Dubious' Deals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404103394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1000 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0404103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 4 KYODO -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange 
said Monday [4 April] it will impose a fine of 21 million yen on 
Kankaku Securities Co. for its involvement in dubious stock 
trading deals in violation of securities rules. 
  The Japan Securities Dealers Association also announced a 
decision to order the second-tier brokerage house to pay a fine 
of 36 million yen for violating securities rules. It is the 
third time for the exchange and the association to punish 
Kankaku Securities for improper dealings. 
  In the latest case, Kankaku Securities was fined for its 
involvement in a questionable practice known as "tobashi" 
between 1990 and 1991 and pledging to compensate clients for 
investment losses between 1985 and 1991. The brokerage is also 
accused of improperly compensating clients over investment 
losses. 
  "Tobashi" is a term for transactions involving the temporary 
transfer of stock that has lost value from one client to another 
in an attempt to cover up the first client's losses. 
  In the latest case, the Finance Ministry has already ordered 
Kankaku Securities to suspend operations in its corporate 
division for 10 days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

