<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa on Diet Debates on 1994 Fiscal Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa on Diet Debates on 1994 Fiscal Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404053294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0511 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0404053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 4 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa told business leaders Monday [4 April] he hopes that 
debates on the 1994 fiscal budget up for Diet approval will be 
expedited, his aides said. Hosokawa made the remark during a 
morning meeting with business leaders, including Eiji Suzuki, 
former head of the Japan Federation of Employers' Associations 
(Nikkeiren), they said. 
  The executives expressed concern that a delay in debates on 
the budget will affect economic recovery, the officials said. 
  The business leaders also urged Hosokawa to make clear the 
government's stance [on] macroeconomic measures, such as tax 
cuts in years beyond fiscal 1994, which began Friday, and an 
additional appropriation for public works projects, they said. 
  Other business representatives at the meeting included 
Shoichiro Toyoda, next president of the Federation of Economic 
Organizations, Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the Japan Chamber of 
Commerce and Industry, Nikkeiren Chairman Takeshi Nagano and 
Masaru Hayami, chairman of the Japan Federation of Corporate 
Executives. 

