<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rate Hikes Curb for Public Utilities Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rate Hikes Curb for Public Utilities Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0104044194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0415 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0104044194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 1 KYODO -- The government, alarmed by 
a host of plans to raise public utilities rates, plans to curb 
such moves, government officials said Friday [1 April]. This 
was decided at a ministerial meeting in response to a request by 
Economic Planning Agency head Manae Kubota that rate hike moves 
be screened carefully by the ministries concerned. 
  Kubota said rate hikes should be restrained particularly at 
a 
time when the domestic economy is showing signs of recovery, 
adding that the government should lay down a "unified view" 
regarding the range and timing of rate increases. 
  Construction Minister Kozo Igarashi urged the government to 
make clear its stance on the matter, the officials said. 
  Local pay telephone call rates went up Friday along with 
medical charges. Public housing, highway and subway 
corporations have announced plans to raise charges in the near 
future. An advisory panel to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
cautioned last week against indiscreet public utilities rate 
hikes. 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told an afternoon 
news conference that the government will study proposed hikes in 
public utilities rates in line with the expected consumer price 
rise of 1.5 percent for fiscal 1994. 
  "The government should make efforts to prevent easy rate 
hikes from leading to the rise in overall consumer prices," the 
top government spokesman added. 
  Takemura said the government will draw up, possibly next 
week, a unified view on a host of plans to raise public 
utilities rates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

