<H3> <TI>   Ban on British Companies `May Be Reviewed' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ban on British Companies `May Be Reviewed' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0304135894 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in Malay 
1300 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0304135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Malay </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said press freedom does not 
mean that people can tell lies and if the Britain press take the 
liberty of telling lies, they must be ready to face the 
consequences. Speaking at a [name indistinct] interview program 
aired by the British (?ITV) network today, the prime minister 
said Malaysia's decision to ban British companies from getting 
new business contracts may be reviewed but such a decision is 
not within his authority. 
  Malaysia imposed the ban following British media reports 
saying Malaysian Government leaders received kickbacks from 
British companies. The ban, which also annulled all business 
agreements, caused British companies to lose billions of ringgit. 
  Speaking at a news conference at the end of his visit to 
Sabah, Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said the federal government had no 
intention of pressuring the Sabah state government when it made 
its decision to rotate the chief minister's post among the three 
main ethnic groups. The move is purely designed to prevent 
undesirable actions by some people. [Mahathir's recording 
indistinct] 
  Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir also talked about tourism in Sabah. 

</TEXT>

