<H3> <TI>   Ministry Discloses Outcome of Border Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Discloses Outcome of Border Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0204152894 Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES in English 2 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0204152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore THE STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Singapore and Malaysia have agreed to meet within 
the next three months to finalise the draft agreement on the 
demarcation of the boundary between the two countries in the 
Straits of Johor. 
  This was announced by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA) 
on Thursday after the sixth Singapore-Malaysia meeting on the 
boundary demarcation held here from Tuesday to Thursday. 
  The Singapore team was led by the senior state counsel in 
the 
Attorney-General's Chambers, Mr S. Tiwari. 
  The leader of the Malaysian delegation was the Ministry of 
Land and Cooperative Development's secretary-general, Mr Azmeer 
Rashid. 
  The MFA statement said the meeting was conducted in "a 
cordial and friendly atmosphere reflecting the close 
relationship and cooperation between the two countries". 
  The two sides carried out negotiations on the draft 
agreement 
to mark precisely the territorial waters boundary, in accordance 
with the Straits Settlement and Johor Territorial Waters 
Agreement 1927. 
  Substantial progress was made and most of the outstanding 
issues were resolved and agreed upon by the two delegations, the 
statement said. It added that both sides agreed to have their 
next meeting in Malaysia. 

</TEXT>

