<H3> <TI>   Kumagai on U.S. Trade Report, Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kumagai on U.S. Trade Report, Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0204014794 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 2 Apr 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0204014794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 1 April Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of international trade 
and industry, told a news conference on 1 April after a cabinet 
meeting that "if an annual report on foreign trade barriers 
recently compiled by the United States is linked to sanctions to 
be imposed in accordance with the Super 301 provision, Japan 
cannot watch idly with indifference." Commenting on the 
inclusion of three priority sectors discussed at the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks in the annual report, he stated, "If 
the Super 301 provision is applied to the three sectors, the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks would collapse. Both Japan 
and the United States need to work to avert such a situation. 
They should resume the framework talks to discuss bilateral 
economic issues in a calm atmosphere and work for a conclusion 
of the framework talks. This is the way to expand and balance 
Japan-U.S. trade." In this way, Mr. Kumagai urged the United 
States not to abuse the annual report and stressed the need for 
resuming the framework talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

