<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Request for Higher Glass Imports Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Request for Higher Glass Imports Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0304141294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0304141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Regarding the issue of expanding plate glass 
imports, which is one of the sectors being discussed at the 
Japane-U.S. framework talks, it has been disclosed that the U.S. 
Government has asked [motometa] the Japanese Government to make 
Japanese glass wholesalers and glass fitters prepare independent 
plans designed to increase their purchases of U.S.-made plate 
glass. In the past, the United States had demanded [yokyu] that 
Japan prepare a plan to buy U.S.-made auto parts, and Japan 
accepted this request. The recent request is the second of its 
kind. Because of this, Japan, which aims to resume the 
framework talks by taking advantage of the announcement of the 
recently approved "foreign economic reform plan outline," is 
faced with a new difficult task. 
  As for an expansion of plate glass purchases, Japan and the 
United States have already signed an accord. The two countries 
are supposed to review this accord at the framework talks. 
  The United States is asking for independent purchasing plans 
prepared by Japanese companies--including aluminum sash and 
prefabricated home builders, plate glass wholesalers, and glass 
fitters. The Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI] 
is strongly rejecting this U.S. demand, saying, "Because there 
is no regulation of plate glass, we cannot give guidance to 
domestic companies asking them to increase their purchases of 
certain goods." 
  There are some 1,000 glass wholesalers and glass fitters in 
Japan, and most of them are small to medium-sized companies. 
Because of this, MITI says that "it is impossible for us to ask 
each company to prepare an independent plan." 
  In January 1992, Japan mapped out an action plan designed to 
help foreign companies make inroads into the Japanese market. 
To implement the plan, MITI has been taking various measures, 
including introducing Japanese wholesalers to U.S. plate glass 
manufacturers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

