<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Sending Election Monitors to South Africa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Sending Election Monitors to South Africa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0404080294 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Apr 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0404080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As of 2 April, it has become definite that Japan 
will send a group of about 40 election monitors to the Republic 
of South Africa to monitor its election of a constituent 
assembly. The elections are scheduled to start on 26 April. 
According to a concrete plan, a group of about 20 monitors 
which is mainly composed of Foreign Ministry personnel and 
civilian volunteers who participated as monitors in the 
Cambodian elections will be sent as independent government 
monitors. Moreover, five monitors will be sent by 
nongovernmental organizations (NGO), and 15 others will go as 
individual participants in the UN Observer Mission to South 
Africa (UNOMSA). 
  The first group of these monitors to be sent by the 
government will leave for South Africa on 8 April. Other 
members will leave around the middle of this month. Moreover, 
Japan also plans to send an advisory election monitoring group 
composed of Diet members. 
  With regard to the upcoming dispatch of the election 
monitors 
group, the government does not plan to apply the UN Peacekeeping 
Operations (PKO) Cooperation Bill. In this connection, the 
election monitors to be sent will not participate directly in 
the UNOMSA, but they will act while maintaining close contacts 
with the UNOMSA. 

</TEXT>

