<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan Emerges for Coalition `Vision Study Group' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plan Emerges for Coalition `Vision Study Group' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0204062894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0204062894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 30 March, a plan emerged among the ruling 
coalition parties to set up a "vision study group" to replace 
the "policy study group" proposed by Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, but which was withdrawn due to opposition from the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] and Sakigake 
[Harbinger]. According to several senior ruling coalition party 
officials, the plan to set up a new study group is aimed at 
coordinating various parties' basic policies regarding such 
general topics as constitutional issues and ideas about how 
Japan ought to be as a nation. They hope to set up the study 
group in April. 
  Former Labor Minister Toshio Yamaguchi (independent), who is 
one of the original proponents of the policy study group, is 
playing a major role in working out plans for the new group. 
Partial changes in the prospectus originally drawn up for the 
policy study group are planned. Changes are to include the 
removal of topics such as that calling for selecting "unified 
candidates" in preparation for future national elections and 
that for cooperation among the ruling coalition parties geared 
toward "formation of a new new party." In addition, study 
subjects are to be changed to more generalized topics instead of 
specific areas, and participation in the study group is to be on 
an individual basis, as a rule. 
  On the morning of 30 March, Yamaguchi met SDPJ Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama at the lower house official residence. 
Yamaguchi explained the new plan and sought his understanding. 
However, Murayama said he believed it is more important to 
resume Diet deliberations on the fiscal 1994 draft national 
budget. 

</TEXT>

